1zq.title: Bayes's Rule: Guide
1zq.clickbait: The Arbital Guide to Bayes's Rule
1zq.text:
Welcome to Arbital's guide to Bayes's Rule!  This is an explanation of [1lz Bayes's Rule] which also demos Arbital's ability to track what you already know and what you want to know, automatically generating sequences of pages that teach a topic.

Before you go on, we'd like to ask you some questions about your background knowledge, which will determine which versions of Arbital pages you see by default.  You will still be able to click on the other tabs to see the other versions, so nothing will be hidden from you.  (You can easily change what the system thinks you know, either by going to the ⋮ button in the light green bar near the word "Edit" and clicking "Show requisites" to see relevant requisite for the current page, or by visiting your [https://arbital.com/requisites/ Arbital requisites page] to see all requisites you've interacted with.)

[comment: ============ Math level? =================]
[multiple-choice(q_math_level):  Different versions of Arbital pages are keyed to different levels of general math ability.  What would you say is your general math level?
a:  I'm bad at math.
-knows: [1r3], [1r5], [1r6], [1r7]
b:  I'm [1r3 not bad at math], but I'm not especially good at it either.
knows: [1r3]
-knows: [1r5], [1r6], [1r7]
c:  I can have [1r5 fun with math], and I won't be anxious if I see a word problem I don't already know how to solve.
knows: [1r3], [1r5]
-knows: [1r6], [1r7]
d:  I am a programmer, physical engineer, or some other profession that calls on me to sometimes [1r6 think in algebra].
knows: [1r3], [1r5], [1r6], [1lx]
-knows: [1r7]
e:  I do [1r7 research-level math].  Hit me with the LaTeX formulas.
knows: [1r3], [1r5], [1r6], [1r7], [1lx], [1r9], [1mh]
]

[comment: ============ Algebra? =================]
%%%!knows-requisite([1r6]):
%%knows-requisite([1r3]):
[multiple-choice(q_algebra):  Would you say that you have an easy time [1lx reading sentences with algebra thrown in?]
a: Yep, seeing an $ab + c^2$ won't scare me.
knows: [1lx], [1r5]
b: Nope.
-knows: [1lx]
]

%%

%%%

[comment: ============ Calculus? =================]
%%%!knows-requisite([1r7]):
%%knows-requisite([1lx]):
[multiple-choice(q_calculus):  Cool!  Do you [1r9 read calculus]?
a: The differential operator is transparent to me.
knows: [1r9]
b: Nope.
-knows: [1r9]
]

%%

%%%

[comment: ============ Logic? =================]
%%%!knows-requisite([1r7]):
%%knows-requisite([1r5]):
[multiple-choice(q_logic):  Can you [1mh read logical notation] like $(A \wedge B) \rightarrow (A \vee B)$?
a: I am connected to the connectors.
knows: [1mh]
b: Nope.
-knows: [1mh]
]

%%

%%%

[comment: ============ Conditional probability? =================]
%%knows-requisite([1mh]):
[multiple-choice(q_conditional_probability):  Do you happen to be familiar enough with [1rj conditional-probability notation] that you can sight-read the difference between $\mathbb P(\mathrm{banana})$ and $\mathbb P(\mathrm{yellow}\mid \mathrm{banana})$?
a: I knew immediately which of those two was "the probability that a banana is yellow". 
knows: [1rj]
b: Nope, sorry.
-knows: [1rj]
]

%%

[comment: ============ Bayes? =================]
%%knows-requisite([1rj]):
[multiple-choice(q_bayes_familiarity):  Uh, are you by any chance already pretty much familiar with Bayes's Rule?
a: Why yes, I am.
knows: [1lz]
b: I know one form of the equation, but I'm interested in learning more about different ways to look at Bayes's Rule and visualize it and so on.
knows: [1lz]
wants: [207]
c: I am not, or I want to see your from-scratch explanation on it regardless.
wants: [1lz]
]

%%


%%%%%knows-requisite([1r5]):

%%!knows-requisite([1lz]):
Thanks for telling us all that!  Then here's our final question:

[comment: ============ How much Bayes? =================]
[multiple-choice(q_how_much_bayes):  How much Bayes do you *want* to know?
a:  Just the basics of Bayes's Rule, without all the frills.
wants: [1lz]
-wants: [207], [25y]
b:  I'd like to try seeing Bayes's Rule from multiple angles and perspectives to obtain a better grasp on it.
wants: [207]
-wants: [25y]
c:  I'm looking for real-world insights, and would like to learn the parts of Bayes's Rule I need for that.
wants: [25y]
-wants: [207]
d:  I'd like to see multiple angles on Bayes's Rule and then read about Bayesian-derived insights.
wants: [207], [25y]
]

%%

Thanks again!  

Now that Arbital knows what you know and what you want to know, it can put together a reading list tailored specifically to your preferences and abilities.  As you finish reading each page on that list, Arbital will ask you if you've understood the presented concepts. If you've understood all of them, click "Yes, I got this. Let's continue!" Arbital will mark the corresponding requisites as "known". If you've only understood some of them, you can click them one by one and then click the "Next" button to move on to the next page.

%%%%wants-requisite([207]):

%%%wants-requisite([25y]):

[https://arbital.com/learn/bayes_rule_details,bayes_update_details,bayes_guide_end Click here to start learning about Bayes's Rule and Bayesian updating!]

%%%

%%%!wants-requisite([25y]):

[https://arbital.com/learn/bayes_rule_details,bayes_guide_end Click here to start learning about Bayes's Rule!]

%%%

%%%%

%%%%!wants-requisite([207]):

%%%wants-requisite([25y]):

[https://arbital.com/learn/bayes_update_details,bayes_guide_end Click here to start learning about Bayesian updating!]

%%%

%%%!wants-requisite([25y]):

%%!knows-requisite([1lz]):

[https://arbital.com/learn/bayes_rule,bayes_guide_end Click here to learn the basics of Bayes's Rule!]

%%

%%knows-requisite([1lz]):

Sorry, we're confused!  It looks like you already know the basics of Bayes's Rule and you didn't ask to learn anything else.  Maybe go back and make different choices above?

%% 

%%%

%%%%

%%%%%

%%%%%!knows-requisite([1r5]):
We're awfully sorry!  The honest truth is that Arbital's Guide to Bayes's Rule is currently set up only to explain things to "people who are good at math" and not to everyone else.  You can go back above and claim to the system that you [1r5 can have fun with math], and follow the trail that results, just to see if maybe you underestimated yourself.  Or check back in later to see if this Arbital Guide has better content next time.  Again, sorry!

%%%%%
